<font color="#FF0000">TO CONTINUE OUR DISCUSSION</font><br>
<tt>Tue Jan  6  5:48:16 US/Eastern 1998
</tt><p>
I too think one of the major reasons for going into<br>
the war was to stop the spread of communism. U.S. govt.<br>
economic policy required countries to supply raw<br>
materials including cheap labor for our economic<br>
expansion. Communism threatened our ability to get<br>
raw goods cheap and have access to get the wealth of<br>
other countires without having to pay top dollar. <br><br>
I also agree that from the Vietnamese perspective (both<br>
North and South) Vietnam was one country and their main<br>
interest was in reunification and the elimination of<br>
foreign dominance in their internal affairs. That is<br>
one reason that China was always less of a supporter <br>
of N. Vietnam than other communist countires. The Vietnamese<br>
have been fighting against Chinese control of Vietnam<br>
for thousands of years.<br><br>
Where I may start to differ from some of you is that I <br>
think that Vietnam has a right to resolve their own<br>
internal conflicts to their satisfaction, even if they <br>
decided to be communist. Vietnam never had aspirations <br>
of control of other countries, except in the short term<br>
for their own self defense. (I did not support their<br>
control over other S.E. Asian countries). I saw the war<br>
as an internal struggle. <br><br>
I also think that as Tom pointed out Diem was put in <br>
place by the CIA and was not a legetimate representative of <br>
any segment of the Vietnamese people. So were those who followed<br><br>
I don't see us as having had a legitimate interest in<br>
going into Vietnam and being involved in a war there.This<br>
was a major component of why I did not support the war.<br>
I also believe that this is a simplification and certainly<br>
not the whole truth, but it is a piece of it.<br><br>
As to communist involvement in the anti-war movement.<br>
There were as many different groups of communists in the<br>
US as there are different groups of republicans. There was<br>
the Communist Party USA and the Socialist Workers Party<br>
to name two, and they could not sit in a room together for<br>
more than 20 minutes without getting into sectarian debate.<br>
There was no foreign control, and in many cases, no foreign<br>
relations on an organizational level. <br><br>
As to the level of public awareness of the Communists in<br>
the anti-war movement. When ever these groups marhed they<br>
brought there banners. They had speakers at the platforms<br>
when they could. It was certainly common knowledge on <br>
the part of those involved in regular protests and anti-war<br>
activities that communists were involved. Again, we did<br>
not care what your ideology was, we cared about what you did<br>
in your daily activity. There was a great deal of internal<br>
resentment to many of these organizations, because they<br>
always presented their points of view, at length, ad nausium<br>
and argued in sectarian divisive ways, while doing less<br>
than their fair share. But they also had some wonderfully hard<br>
workers who did good work. Like the Democrates and Republicans<br>
there are some good ones, and some bad ones.<br><br>
I do not see a great contradiction between wanting the<br>
Communists to control VN and wanting the war to end. The<br>
issue is how did you want vicotry to come to the Communist<br>
forces and at what expense. As far as I could tell, <br>
Ho Chi Min had the most popular support<br>
of any leader, and he was a person that therefore should<br>
have been the head of whatever government there was. <br><br>
As for people working at a high level of committment being <br>
only communists, some of the most dedicated and hard working <br>
people were in organizations like Woman's International<br>
league for Peace and Freedom, the American Friends Service Committee,<br>
Committee for a SANE Nuclear Policy, and the National COuncil of Churchs.<br>
They were clearly non Communist organizations, but were major<br>
players in helping organize and motivate people.<br><br>
As for my own personal beliefs and where I am coming from...<br>
I like to not know where someone is &quot;coming from&quot; because<br>
it makes me think about what they are saying and it makes<br>
it harder for me to put someone in a box and discount their<br>
ideas. I would love to know morea bout all of those who I am<br>
talking with, but I will refrain from asking.<br><br>
Some questions, how do you define communism and why does<br>
it matter how any of us define ourselves. Don't ideas<br>
stand on?
